{"/service/ndnp/wyu/batch_wyu_hartville_ver01/data/sn86072160/00514150461/1924011501/0943.xml":{"full_text":"\u25a0jESDAY, JANUARY 15, 1924\nOil :t Finance S Bonds Stocks Grain Livestock S AU Markets\n\u25a0Materials Being Moved to\nHiawatha Dome for Test\nThe Initial step In carrying out\nextensive wilt? catting program\nWycmlng field?, was taken this\nwhen the Midwest R*>fln\ncompany began the work of\nfield material from Rock\nto the Hiawatha deme,\nthorough lefts are plannc!\nthe coming spring and sum-\nmonths. This equipment. It le\nwill be Immediately\n\u25a0\u25a0\u2019spotted\" and Installed, and thus\n\u25a0Qjieced In position for operation with\nbreak in severe weather condl-\nThe Midwest recently, through a\nof lease by F. r. McCarthy,\ncontrol cf 2,360 teres on\nHiawatha structure and it is\n[Trade News in' Commodity\nMarkets of Country\nOU.\nTULBA, Jan. 15.\u2014Production In\nthe Burbank pool is expected to be\nIncreased from 70,000 to 110.000\nbarrels a day as a result of a ds*\nclsion of Midcontinent oil operators\nto lift the ban on Burbank drilling.\nFifty wells on pay sand tn Osage\nand Kay counties are being shot\nin and 50 new locations will be\ndrilled immediately, according to E.\nR. Perry of Cosden and company,\nchairman of the operators com*\nmittee.\nHOUSTON. Jan. 15.\u2014The new\nprices of Coastal crude oil estab\nlished as a result of recent advances\nby Gulf Pipe Line and Humble Oil\ncompanies are >1.50 for grade A\nand 11.25 for grade B. The latter\ngrade is posted only in the Blue\nRidge, Pierce Junction and Hull\nfields of Texas.\nDENVER, Jan. 15.\u2014The Union\nOil company of California has an\nnounced it will shortly spud in its\nsecond well on the Wellington\nDome near Fort Collins. Colo. A\nminiature oil boom is now sweeping\nnorthern Colorado as a result of the\nsuccess of the first well in that\nfield.\nMarket Gossip anti Briefs\nOn Operations in Oil Fields\nCotton Futures Soar.\nNEW YORK. Jon. 15.\u2014Cotton ad\nvanced 60 to 75 points in the local\nmarket today on publication of cen\nsus bureau reports showing con\nsumption of 461,560 balco for De*\n\u00a9ember. March contracts in the lo\ncal market advanced to $34-25 com\npared with $33.25, the lower level\nof yesterday.\nWyoming Oils.\nNEW YORK, Jan. 15.\u2014Prices of\nWyoming oils at 2 p. m. today were\nlisted on the New York curb as fol\nlows:\nStandard Oil Indiana 66*4; Glen\nrock 44; Mountain Producers 18%:\nMutual 12%; New York 12%; Salt\nC\u2019rcek. 23.\nSouth Dakota Test.\nStarting through a red beds' sur\nface exposure on the Martin Valley\nranch about seven miles northeast\nof Hot Springs, S. D., the Mutual\n'Oil company is spudding a new test\nand is now down 80 feet. Drilling\ncommenced last Friday with u\n12%-lnch hole at the top. It is\nthought the Madison limo will be\npicked u pat between 900 and 1.000\nFOHTGOLLINS\nMENVISUORS\n(Continued From Tago One)\nCasper and Fort Collins, Casper be\ning named after Casper Collins, and\nthe Colorado city being named after\nthe father of the same man.\nAttorney James P. Kern, secre\ntary of the Salt Creek Producers'\nConservation committee, had for\nhis talk the subject of \"Land and\nTitles\". \"If your present oil indi\ncations fulfill their promises, you\nare in for n visitation of lawyers,\"\nhe said, referring to the oil business\nas it is related to the lawyer.\n\"A comprehensive tax reduction\nprogram would be an excellent\nthing for the oil industry,\u201d the at\ntorney stated. \"The Mellon plan\nwould seem to be a step in the right\ndirection and an entering wedge. It\nwould be well for the citizens of\nboth Colorado and Wyoming to\nurge such a measure on congress.\"\nB. L. Scherck. Casper realtor, dis\ncussed real estate as its rise and\nfall is effected by oil or lack of it.\nHe advised Fort Collins to take up\na zoning system and to maintain n.\nstrong real estate board with the\nend in view of keeping out land\nsharks.\nReferring to Casper's earlier per\niod. W. 3. Kimball, owner of two\nCasper drug stores, said. \u201cWhile I\nwould not willingly forego having\nhad the experience of those \u2019goo<\nold days.' yet it must be confessed,\n\u2019peaking strictly from a mercenary\nPoint cf view as a merchant ana\nProperty holder that however g>odj\n*be best Livestock town may be*\nths transition of sooh oom-\nupon this land that the corporation\nwil! push envelopment work. The\nMcCarthy holdings cover sections\n12, 14, 23 and 34-13-100 and are to\nbe drilled on a seven per cent oil\nand five per cent gas royalty basis.\nThe Midwest has also taken up\nother acreage on both the H'awatha\nand Vermillion domes with the view\nof extensive development. These sec\ntions of comparatively new terri\ntory are located about 55 miles\nsouth of Rock Springs and situated\neight miles north of the Colorado\nstate line.\nVarious wild cat operations are.\nit is said, to b\u00ab undertaken by the\nwith the coming of warmer\nweather.\nDry Goods.\nATLANTA, Jan. 15.\u2014Atlanta job\nbers have launched a vigorous sale\ncampaign through co-operative ad\nvertising and weekly circularizing\nof every well rated retailer in the\ntrade territory. Mid-winter buying\nfor cash is reflected in ordets now\ncoming in from small rural stores.\nGrain.\nSAN FRANCISCO, Jan. 15.\nPlanting of wheat, barley and oats\nhas been retarded by dry weather.\nEarly sown grain has not thriven\nand reseeding will be necessary.\nEggs.\nPORTLAND, Jan. 15.\u2014A further\ncut of 3 cents a dozen has been\nmade in the price of eggs hero fol\nlowing another drop in the south.\nPrices now range between 33 cents\nfor pullets and 36 cents for extras.\nSteel.\nCLEVELAND, Jan. 15. The\nHanna Furnace company has re\nlighted Its furnaces at Dover which\nhave been Idle since September.\nThe Republic Iron and Steel com\npany will resume January 31 at 13\nmills at Niles, idle since June 30.\npicked up at between 900 and 1,000\ndown waiting on several additional\njoints of conductor pipe.\nTo Geologise Counties\nA thorough geological investiga\ntion Is to be made of Platte. Gosh\nen and Laramie counties this com\ning spring by the state geologist.\nAlbert B. Bartlett. The fact\nthat tho Salt Creek oil bearing\nsands seem to be in evidence in the\nnew Wellington field north of Fort\nCollins. Colo., and which indicates\nan extension of these sands through\nthe above named counties, is the\nprimary factor behind the investi\ngation.\nMcCoy Promoted\nClark McCoy, Lost Soldier field\nsuperintendent of the Bair Oil com\npany, has been given charge of the 1\nBair offices at Rawlins, and suc\nceeds Mr. Gettemy, resigned.\nlias Refining Course\nNight school classes in the prin\nclples of petroleum refining have\nbeen started in Rawlins. In charge\nof instruction is D. B. Mapes, chief\nchemist at the Parco refinery.\nmunity into a seething, boiling, tu\nmultuous oil producing and refin\ning industrial city in tho short\nspace of one decade, with unfailing\npay-days aggregating many m?\nHons of dollaxs a year occurring in\nregular installments several times a\nmonth instead of the old possibility\nthat a few hundred thousand dol\nlars might be distributed twice a\nyear, is an experience nev-i.* to bo\nforgotten by these participating in\nit.\"\nBusinesses already established\nwhero the management Is adjusted\nto changing conditions, have every\nadvantage in maintaining a lead,\nncco.-ding to Mr. Kimball who drew\nhis conclusion from watching sev\neral Casper firms grow with the\ncity.\nCharles McMillan of Fort Collins\ngave a word of welcome for the\nCasperites. \u201cWe want you to come\ndown to Fort Collins,\u201d he \u00bboid.\nH. G. Shaw, gave a vivid picture\nof the city from which the dele\ngates had come, told of its paved\nstreets, its wonderful scenic ef\nfects, Its bigness and prngrveslve\nness \"It Is a good town, a bj-r town,\na coming Casper, and wh are\nstronger for it than native horse\nradish\" he remarked.\nBoth the girls' and boys' quartets\nof the Natrona County high school\nentertained those gathered at th\"\nluncheon today with a number of\nsongs.\nThe Fort Collins delegates and\nthe members of the Caspe? Cham\nber of Commerce will meet this eve\nnlng at 8 o\u2019clock in the court room\nof the court house for a program\nprepared by the Petroleum club\nwhich xvjll go more into detail re\ngarding oil matters and handl'nrr an\noil city than the program this noon.\nI For results try a Tribune Classi\nfied Ad.\nNew York Stocks\nNEW YORK STOCKS\u2014 LAST\nSALE\nAllied Chemical A Dye ex div 70%\nAmerican Can... 106%\nAmerican Car and Foundry. 163 B\nAmerican International Corp 24\nAmerican Locomotive 73%\nAmerican Smelting and Refg 58%\nAmerican Sugar 54%\nAmerican T. and T. 129%\nAmerican Tobacco 143%\nAmerican Woolen 75%\nAnaconda Copper 36%\nAtchison 98\nAtl., Gulf and West Indies 14%\nBaldwin Locomotive.l23%\nBaltimore and Ohio 57%\nBethlehem Steel- 54\nCalifornia Petroleum 25%\nCanadian Pacific 147%\nCenertal leather\u2014 15%\nCerro de Pasco Copper 46\nChandler Motors 61\nChesapeak and Ohio 72%\nChicago and Northwestern 50%\nChicago, MIL, A St Paul pfrt 26%\nChicago, R. I. and Pi\u00a3c. 24%\nChile Copper 27%\nChino Copper 13\nConsolidated Gas 63\nCorn Products 157%\nCosden 0i135%\nCrucible Steel ex div. 65%\nCuba Cane Sugar pfd. 61%\nErie 25%\nFamous Players Lasky 70%\nGeneral Asphalt 44%\nGeneral Electric 199\nGeneral Motors 14%\nGreat Northern pfd. 56%\nGulf States Steel 81\nIllinois Central 102%\nInspiration Copper 25%\nInternational Harvester 83%\nInt. Mer. Marine pfd 30%\nInternational Paper 33\nInvincible OH 15%\nKelly Springfield Tire 83\nKannecctt Copper 34%\nLima Locomotive 66\nLouisville and Nashville ex JI. 88%\nMack Truck 86\nMarland 03 37%\nMaxwell Motors 14\nMiddle States Oil 6\nMissouri, Kan and Tear new 11%\nMissouri Pacific pfd. 31%\nNew York Central 101%\nN. Y\u201e N. H. and Hartford 17%\nNorfolk and Western 104%\nNorthern Pacific 53%\nPacific Oi! 40\nPan American Petroleum B 53%\n'Pe