26\nColumbine .10 .12\nCentral Pipe \u20142.00 2.10\ni Consolidated Royalty 1.34 1.26\nCow GulcU .03 .04\nDomino .\u2014.lO .13\ni Elkhorn .03 ,C 4\ni E. T. Williams. 43 .50\nFrants 3.00 6.00\n1 Gatea .07 .09\n1 Jupiter .00% .01\nj Kinney Coastal .18 .20\nLance Creek Royalty.. .01 .02\nMountain A Gulflso 1.55\nMosher Oklaloo.oo 125.00\nNew York Oil \u201412.00 14.00\nPreston .00% .01\nPicardy \u2014.03 .04\nRed Bank 6.00 8.00\nRoyalty A Producers .09 .10\nSunset .02 .03\nTom Bell Royalty.o2 .03\nWestern Exploration 3.25 3.30\n1 Western Stites .30 .33\nWyo-Kan.so .55\n3 Y. Oil .08 .10\nNEW YORK CURB CLOSING\nMountain Producers 18.50 18.75\nGlenrock OU .43 .50\nSalt Creek Prda2B.2B 22.50\n1 Salt Creek Cons 9.35 9.75\nProd. and. Refrs 35.25 35.75\nCosden 35.00 35.37\n1 Mutual \u201412.00 12.12\nS O. Indiana CGI3 66.25\n3 Cities Service Com. 149.00 150.00\ni\n3 Livestock\nChicago Prices.\nCHICAGO. Jan. 15.\u2014(U- S, De\npartment of Agriculture).\u2014Hoge\u2014\nReceipts 68.000; moderately active.\n5 to 10 cents lower; mostly 5 cents\n1 off to small puckers and shippers;\nC big packers inactive; bulk good and\nchoice 240 to 300 pound butchers\n|7.30(97.35{ top $7.35; desirable 150\nto 225 pound averages mostly s7@\n7.25; packing bows largely $6,600\n2 6.75; killing pig* slow, weak; bulk\n4 strong weight $6.5006 75; heavy\n3 weight hogs $7.1607.35; medium\n$7.1007.30; light $6.9007.25; light\nv light $6.500 7.10; packing sows\n3 smooth $6.6506.85; packing sows\n4 rough $6-50 0 6.65; slaughter pigs\ni $5.6006.75.\n3 Cattle\u2014Receipts 15.000; killing\n4 classes slow at Monday's extreme\ndecline; quality, less desirable; rela-\n\u25a02 tlvely tew fed'steers here of value\nto soli above $10.50; $8.25 to $9.76\n4 description predominate; early top\n4 matured steers $10.55; average\nweight round 1,500 pounds: several\nloads weighty steers SIOO 10.75;\nchoice yearlings scarce; steady coun\ntry demand narrow; most fat sows\n$4.5007.76; short fed beef heifers\n$506.75; canners and cutters $2.50\n03.25 mostly; bulls uneven; few\nweighty sausage offerings above\n$5; plainer and lighter kind down\nward to 4.50 and below: vealers\nmostly fifty under Monday's average\nupturn; packers buying at S9OIO,\naccording to weight and quality\nshipping demand meagre at $10,500\n11.00.\nSheep\u2014Receipts 17,000; fat lambs\nsteady to strong; sheep and feed\ning lambs around steady; bulk fat\nwooled lambs $13013.65; early top\nto shippers $13.70; some held high\ner: clipped lambs around 90 pounds\n$11.25; medium weight yearling\nwethers $11; aged wethers $9; handy\nweight fat ewes $8; feeding lambs\nmostly $12.50012.75.\nOmaha Quotations.\nOSLIHA, Neb., Jan. 15.\u2014<U. S.\nDepartment of Agriculture.)\u2014Hogs\n\u2014Receipts, 20.000; market slow;\nearly sales, 10015 c lower: bulk 220\nto 825 pound butchers, $6.8506.90;\ntop, $6.95; 180 to 210 pound weight,\n$6.7006.85; packing grades, mostly\n$6.50; few smooth grades, $6.60;\naverage cost yesterday, $6.87:\nweight, 246.\nCattle\u2014Receipts, 10.000; market\nmoderately active; killing quality\nplain; bulk early sales fed steers\nand yearlings. $7.7508.76; looks\nsteady with yesterday's genera!\nmarket; best weighty steers, $9.10;\nhandy weight steers on yearling\norders, $9.25; better grades fed she\nstock, canners and cutters, steady\nwith yesterday's decline; others\nsteady to weak; bulls, strong; veal\ners, 25060 c lower; Stockers nnd\nfeeders, strong; spots higher; bulk\nbutcher cows and heifers, $4,000\n6.25; canners and cutters. $2,250\nj 8.50; vealers to packers, $9.0009.50;\n5 outsiders paying upward to $10.50;\nbologna bulls, mostly $4.0004.60;\nstockers and feeders, $6.0007.25;\ntop feeders, $7.90.\nSheep\u2014Receipts, 14,000; market\nfairly active; fat lambs about\nsteady: early sales wooled lambs.\nJ mostly $12.75012.85; top, $13.00;\n5 clipped lambs, $10.80; sheep, weak\nto 10015 c lower; light and handy\nweight ewes, $7.5007.75; feeding\n1 lambs, slow.\nDenver Prices.\nI DENVER. Colo., Jan. 15.\u2014<U. S.\nDepartment of Agriculture.)\u2014Hogs\n\u2014Receipts, 4,900; slow; bulk unsold;\nI early sales, 10c lower; several loads\nI medium to choice 190 to 220 pound\nI averages, $6.75 to $6.95; packing\nsows, steady, mostly $5.76.\nr Cattle Receipts. 2,500; calves,\n100; steady; medium to fairly good\nbeef steers, $7.85 to $8.35; several\nloads good heifers, $7.25 to $7.50;\nmedium to good cows, $5.25 to $6.25;\ni- canners, mostly $2.00; beef bulls,\no $4.00 to $4.50; bologna bulls, $3.25 to\nI- $3.50; four loads b?st feeders, $7.85.\nr Sheep\u2014Receipts, 7,300; few sales\nf fat lambs, steady; two loads 90\ni- pound averages, $12.60 freight paid:\n5 two cars 84 pound weights, $12.60\ne freight paid; no sheep nor feeding\nlambs sold early.\nSTOCK PRICES\nTURNUPWARD\nIrregular Recovery Takes\nPlace In Session of Spora\ndic Seiling\nNEW TOnK. Jan. IS\u2014stock\nPrices made irregular recovery from\nyesterday\u2019s weakness in today\u2019\u00ae leas\nactive session. sporadic selling took\nplace during the day in various sec\ntions of the list in response to high\ner money rates and Washington de\nvelopments believed to be unfavor\nable to the early passage of a tax\nreduction bill. Foreign exchanges\nmade substantial recovery on the\ndecision of the French cabinet to In\ncrease taxes and balance the bud\nget. Sale approximated 1,000,000\nshares.\nNEW YORK, Jan. 15.\u2014Further\nliquidation took place at the open\ning of today's stock market, giving\nInitial prices a \u2022.\u2022cactlonary appear\nance. There were a few strong\nspots, notably Consolidated Cigar\nand General Electric, each of which\nmoved up a point. Eoases as a rule,\nwere limited to fractions but they\nspread over a wide list.\nGood buying support was forth\ncoming In the first hour, much of\nIt short covering, and the general\nlist started to swing upward again.\nMaracaibo Oil. which moved up\nmore than four points yesterday,\nadded I\u20194 points today touching a\nnew record price of 33%. Consoli\ndated Cigars preferred moved up\n2% in further reflection of its com\ning merger with LorlHard. Initial\nfractional losses In the standard in\ndustrials were soon made up but\nsome of the food shares were heavy,\nSouth Porto Rican Sugar, Ameri\ncan Beet Sugar and American Cot\nton Oil preferred certificates drojy\nping n point or no. Reading, sell\ning ex-rights, was quoted at 57.\nForeign exchanges opened firm.\nSpecial weakness cropped out In\nseveral special stocks after the im\nmediate requirement of the shorts\nbad been met. The Pan-American\nissues. General Asphalt, Marland.\nU. S. Cast Iron Pipe. American\nTobacco, Inspiration Copper and\nColorado and Southern common and\nsecond preferred yielded ono to two\npoints. Elsewhere the market held\nsteady. A brisk demand then arose\nfor the Reading issues, Bt. Paul pre\nferred, Union Pacific and several\npopular Industrials, which brought\nabout another upward movement\nbefore noon. Call money opened at\n4% par cent.\nThe market wavered for a time\nwhen United States cast iron pipe\nwas subjected to renewed selling,\nfalling to 66*4: a loss of 3%. A\nlater active Inquiry for the low\npriced railroads, especially tho Erles.\nMissouri Pacific preferred. St. Louis\nand San Francisco, preferred. Texas\nand Pacific and Wheeling and Lake\nErie preferred, which rose 1 to 2\npoints, stiffened prices elsewhere.\nTho closing was Irregular. Five\nper cent call money and a 3% point\ndrop in Continental Can brought\nabout renewed selling of aome of the\nspeculative favorites in tho late\ndealings.\nForeign Exchange\nNEW YORK. Jan. 15\u2014Foreign\nexchanges steady; quotations in\ncents:\nGreat Britain demand 424%: cab\nles 425%; sixty day bills on banks\n422%. France demauid 4.07%; cables\n4.08. Germany demand .000000000-\n022;: cables .000000000022. Holland\ndemand 37.15; cables 37.20; Nor\nway 14.17; Sweden 26.14; Denmark\n17.37; Switzerland 17.29; Spain 12.61:\nGreece 1.97: Poland .000010; Czccho.\nSlovakia 2.91; Jugo Slavia 1.13%;\nAustria .0014. Rumania .50; Argen\ntine 33.00; Brazil 11.12; Montreal\n9vi \u2014-\u20141\nSilver\nNEW YORK. Jan. 15.\u2014Bar silver,\n63. Mexican dollars, 48.\nPotatoes\nCHICAGO, Jan. 15.\u2014Potatoes\nabout steady; receipts, 61 cars;\ntotal U. 8. shipments, 592; Wiscon\nsin sacked round whites, >1.2001.40:\nfrozen, SI.OOO 1.15: bulk, $1.4001.50;\ndustles, $1.65; Michigan bulk round\nwhites, $1.50; Minnesota sacked\nrount whites, $1.1501.30: sacked\nsand land Ohlos, $1.1001.15.\nMoney\nNEW YORK. Jan. 15\u2014Call money\nfirmer; high, 6; low, 4%; ruling rate,\n4*4: closing bld. 5; offered at 6%:\nlast loan, 5; call loans against ac\nceptances, 4; time loans, easy; mixed\ncollateral, 60-90 days, 4%; 4-6\nmonths, 4%; prime commercial\npaper, 4% 05.\nCotton\nNEW YORK, Jan. 15.\u2014Spot eot\nton steady; middling $84.30.\nFlour.\nMINNEAPOLIS, Minn., Jan, 15.\n\u2014Flour unchanged; bran $33,300\n827.00,\nGRAN PRICES\nARE STRONGER\nCorr, Prices Touch New High\nFor Season. Wheat\nCloses Firm\nCHICAGO, Jan. 15\u2014Com soared\ntoday, all deliveries reaching a new\nhigh pric\u00ab record for ths season.\nMuy oats also overtopped the sea\neon record. The day\u2019s beet prices\nwere attained tn the last half hour\nof business. Com closed unsettled\n1 to 1%01% cents net higher. May\n78% 0% to 78%.\nCHICAGO, Jan. 15\u2014With only 98\ncarloads of corn received in Chi\ncago today when the big winter\nmovement of ths corn crop should\nbe in progress, all grain prices\nshowed firmness during the early\ndealings. Very, little corn was\nbeing offered to arrive, and specu\nlative sellers were decidedly cau\ntious. On the other hand, some\ntraders were expressing aggressive\nbullish opinions and were apparently\nanticipating a bulge in prices before\nthe close. After opening at %c\nlower to %o advance, May 77% to\n77%, corn scored a moderate gen\neral upturn.\nlu the latter transactiona, corn\ncontinued to develop strength. It\nwas pointed out that although the\nweather had been perfect for a\nweek, there had been no country\nselling of importance.\nBuying orders for the northwest\nhelped mako the wheat market\ntend upward a little. The opening,\nwhich varied from %c off to %c\nup. May 1.05% to 108%, and July\n1 06%, was followed by u slight set\nback and then something of a rally.\nSubsequently reports of lack of\nsnow covering for winter wheat had\na bullish effect, and so too did the\ncorn market advance. Wheal\nclosed firm to %c net higher,\nMay 1.09 to 1.09% and July 107%.\nOats paralleled the action of\nwheat, opening %c lower to a shade\nadvance. May 46% to 46%, and\nlater hardening a trifle all around.\nProvisions were weak, reflecting\na drop in the value of hogs.\nOpen High Low Close\nWHEAT\u2014\nMay 1-08% 1.09% 1.08% 1.09\nJuly 1.06% 1.07% 1.06% 1.07%\nSept. .1.06 1.06% 1.06 1.06%\nCORN\u2014\nMay .77% .79% .77% .78%\nJuly .78% .80% .78% .79%\nSep. .79% .80% .79% .80%\nOATS\u2014\nMay .46% .47% .46% .47%\nJuV 44% .45% .44% .45%\nSep. .43% .43% .43% .43%\nLARD\u2014\nJan. 11.92 11.95 11.82 11.87\nMay \u201411.90 11.90 11.72 11.82\nRIBS\u2014\nJan. a.85\nMay 9.95 9.95 9.87 9.90\nCHICAGO, Jan. 15\u2014Wheat num\nber 2 red 1.13%; number 2 hard\n1-12%.\nCorn number 2 mixed 77%c; num\nber 2 yellow 78c.\nOats number 2 white 40% \u00a943c;\nnumber 3 white 46047 c.\nRye number 73%c; barley 640\n79c: timothy seed $6,500 $8.50: clover\nseed $18.00023.50: lard $12.25; ribs\nsixty pound average $9.87.\nMetals\nNEW YORK, Jan. 15.\u2014Copper,\neasy: electrolytic, spot and nearby,\n12%\u00ae%: futures, 12%@%.\nTin, firm: spot and nearby. 49.37;\nfutures, 48.87.\nIron, steady; prices unchanged.\nLead, steady; spot, 7.9008.25.\nZinc, quiet; East St. Louis spot\nand nearby, 6.300 6.35.\nAntimony. s|\u00bbot, 10.00.\nSagar\nNEW YORK, Jan. 15.\u20141 n refined\nsugar a fair business was noted.\nPrices were unchanged at 8.25 to\n8.60 for fine granulated. Refined\nfutures nominal.\nSugar futures closed steady. Ap\nproxima