Bell Tel.. 7s 108 107% 107%\nPacific Gas and Electric 5s 91% 91 91%\nPenn. IL R. Gen 5s 99% 99% 99%\nSlnc\u2019alr Con Oil col., 7s 94% 94% 94%\nSouthern Pacific cv.. 4s 92% 92% 92%\nUnion Pacific First 4a 91% 91% 91%\nU. S. Rubber 5a 85% 85% 85%\nUtah Power and Light, 5s BB% 88% 88%\nWestern Union. 6%s 109% 109% 109%\nWestinghouse Elect ria. 7s 107% 107% 107%\nWilson Co., cv.. 6s 96% 96% 95%\nVIOLENTQUE\nIN JAPAN ON\n(Continued From Page One)\nures, and to obtain information re\ngarding the extent of the damage.\nThe stock market suspended op\nerations owing to the failure of\ncommunicat ions.\nDAMAGE NOT\nYET KNOWN\nOSAKA. Japan. Jan. 15\u2014(By The\nAssociated Press)\u2014The serious\nearthquake which began at 6:45 a.\ntn. today around the Nagano pre\nfecture is supposed to have been\ncentered at Matsumoto. The dam\nage is not known here.\nToklo and Nagoya were affected\nby strong tremors. Osaka and\nKyoto felt the shocks elightly.\nNagano prefecture is situated on\na tableland 1n the central part of\nthe main island of Japan. Silk is\nthe most Important industry* of the\nregion. There also is extensive\nfarming and forestry. Matdumoto\nIs a prosperous commercial city,\nwith heavy transactions In cocoons\nand silk worm eggs.\nSHANGHAI HEARS\nDISASTER REPORTS\nSHANGHAI, Jan. 15\u2014(By The\nAssociated Frees\u2014Extensive dam\nage, including destruction of houses\nat Numadzu and interruption of all\ncommunication In the vicinity of\nToklo and Yokohama has followed\nin tho wake of a heavy earthquake\nwhich occurred this morning, ac\ncording to advices received from\ntho affected district by the Nihon\nDempo, a Japanese press associa\ntion here.\nTh<- reports state that the emper\nor and the empress are safe at Num\nadzu, despite widespread destruc\ntion In that city, in which many\nhomes are said to have been shaken\ndown. The imperial villa, located\nat Numadzu, was not damaged\nhowever, the reports state.\nThe area of greatest damage Is\nsaid to have been between the towns\nof Gotemba. which is about 80 miles\nsouthwest of Tokio. nnd Koozu. and\nsouthward in the vicinity of Hakon e\niHtordlng to reports received over\na single railway line kept in opera\ntion by the Kobe railway bureau be\ntween Toklo and Honshu.\nSlight damage was suffered by the\ndistrict between Tokio and Kooxu.\nadvices from thia source stated. The\nquake waa felt at Nagoya, about 200\nmiles southwest of Tokio. in the\nprovince of Owari, and in Shizuoka,\nin Suruga province, along Suruga\nbay;\nThe meterologlcal observatory at\nOsaka announced after the quake\nthat the width of the oscillations re\ncorded by the seismograph by the\nearth shock was 39 5-10 millimeters.\nTho quake lasted for 14 minutes.\nThe seismological .center apparently\nnan off the Klshu coast, it was\nstated.\nNO AMERICANS\nAMONG KILLED.\nWASHINGTON. Jan. 15Jeffer\nson Cajfery, American charge at\nTokio cabled today that Tokio and\nYokohama. \"Buffered a severe earth\nquake shock this morning-.\u2019\u2019 caus\ning temporary suspension of rail\nway service, the water supply, tho\nelectric lighting system, and telo\ngraphic and telephonic communica\ntion. He said Tokio newspapers esti\nmated that fifty persons were\nkilled.\nNo Americans were reported\namong the dead. Frederick D. K.\nLec\u2019eroq, second secretary of the\nAmerican embassy suffered a frac\ntured wrist. Mr. Caffery spJd. gdd-\nIng that with this exception the\nstaffn of the embassy and th\u00ae con\nsulate general had suffered no in-\nJun*.\nA similar report was received\nfrom Consul General Stewart at To\nkohama.\nWASHINGTON, Jan. 15. The\nlatest Japanese earthquake as re\ncorded on the Georgetown univer\nsity seismograph continued for al-\nI most two hours and reached its\nmaximum intensity between 6:45 a.\nm. and 6:30 a. in., Tokio time.\nFather Tondarf, Jn charge of the\nPAGE EIGHT\ninstrument reported that tho first\ntremors were picked up at 6:15 a.\nm. and that the)* continued until\nabout 8 a. m.\nEAST ANO WEST SPLIT\nHONORS IN LAUNCHING\nGRIDE LEAGUE SEASON\nThe opening games tn the Grade\nSchool Basketball league were\nplayed Monday evening at the high\nschool gym when the West Casper\nboys defeated East Casper, 4 to 3,\nand the East Casper girls won from\nthe West Casper girls, 10 to 0.\nThe fact that only 10 minute\nhalves were played accounts for tho\nlow scores.\nThe league schedule for tho rest\nof the week is as follows:\nTuesday\u2014North vs. Park, girls\u2019\nand boys teams.\ni Wednesday\u2014Central v\u00ab. Mills,\nboys only.\ni Thursday\u2014East vs. Park, boys\u2019\nand girls' teams.\ni Friday\u2014West vs. Central, boys\u2019\nand girls* teams.\nLast night\u2019s scores were as fol\ni Iowa:\nEast Boys (3) Pos. West (4)\nRichie Campbell\nForward\nCrowe Eads\nForward\nJones-Finn Zaires\nCenter\nSchwartz Smith\nGuard\nMagneson Culver\nGuard\nEast Girls (10) Pos. West (0)\nNellie Kerr...Huzeldedr Hayes\nRight Forward\nMargaret Grlssenger..lrma Hansen\nLeft Forward\nGladys Searles Elsie Knight\nCenter\nPauline Cozad..Muriel Greer\nRight Guard\nEllen Logue Roberta Brownl*o\nLeft Guard\nHelen Mclker Lorene Galleager\nRight Center\nMayer Divorce Is\nGranted. By Court;\n$20,000 Divided\nChristina Maher was granted an\nabsolute divorce from W. J. Maher\nthis afternoon by Judge IL IL Rose\nin district court and an equal divi\nsion in Casper and Wisconsin prop\nerty valued at $20,000. She is also\nto have $25 per month alimony and\nattorney\u2019s fees and costs.\nThe case was contested by the de\nfendant and bitterly fought, the in\ntroduction of evidence consuming\nthe greater part of the day.\nOtto Spratte of Denver is here on\nbusiness having arrived this morn\ning.\nAre You Interested\nI In the Mellon Plan\nIf you are interested to know\nhow the Mellon Plan will af\nfect your business either as an\nindividual or corporation, I will\nbe glad to explain it to you.\nC H. Reimerth\nCertified Public\nAccountant\nIncome Tax Service\nI 401 O-S Bldg.; Phone 767","